PHP SDK for interacting with the Deta API. Provides a Deta client class for accessing Deta Base (NoSQL database) and Deta Drive (file storage).

### Usage
```php
use tuefekci\deta\Deta;
$deta = new Deta('your_project_id', 'your_api_key');
$my_base = $deta->base('my_base');

// Insert, get, update, delete, and query items in Base
$my_base->insert(['name' => 'Alice', 'age' => 30]);
$item = $my_base->get('abc123');
$my_base->update('abc123', ['name' => 'Bob']);
$my_base->delete('abc123');
$items = $my_base->query(['age' => ['lt' => 40]]);

// File operations via Drive
$my_drive = $deta->drive('my_drive');
$my_drive->put('file.txt', 'Hello, world!');
$content = $my_drive->get('file.txt');
$files = $my_drive->list();
```

Queue implementation for use with Deta Base, written in TypeScript. Provides a simple FIFO queue backed by Deta's NoSQL database with configurable TTL and queue name.

### Usage
```typescript
import { Queue } from 'deta-queue';
import { Deta } from 'deta';

const deta = Deta(process.env.DETA_PROJECT_KEY);
const queue = new Queue(deta);

async function main() {
    await queue.empty();
    const items = ["test1", "test2", "test3", "test4", "test5"];
    for (let element of items) {
        await queue.push(element);
    }
    const item = queue.pop(1);
    console.log(item);  //=> 'test1'
}
```

Published as npm package `deta-queue`.

PHP wrapper for the DigitalOcean API. All methods are supported. Documentation for the DigitalOcean API can be found at digitalocean.com/api. Automatically generated phpDoc lives at remmelt.github.com/DigitalOcean-PHP-Class.

### Example Usage
```php
require_once('DigitalOcean.class.php');
$ocean = new \DigitalOceanApi\DigitalOcean('client_id_here','api_key_here');
$droplets = get_object_vars($ocean->getDroplets());
$i=0;
$x=0;
foreach ($droplets as $drops) {
	if (!is_array($drops)) {
		echo $i . '. Status: ' . $drops . '<br />';
	} else {
		echo $i . '. Name: ' . $drops[$x]->name . '<br />';
		echo $i . '. IP: ' . $drops[$x]->ip_address . '<br />';
		$x++;
	}
	$i++;
}
```

The above will result in something like:
```
0. Status: OK
1. Name: your-droplet-name
1. IP: your-droplet-ip
```
